    "body": "### Problem\n\nhttps://github.com/user-attachments/assets/abdaad31-add2-4fce-9980-9cfad40c0452\n\nIf `autoindent` inserts indentation on a line and then you press `<Esc>` without typing anything on that line, the whole indentation should be deleted again. However, if `virtualedit` is set to `onemore`, only a single \"unit\" of indentation is deleted instead of the whole indentation. When using tabs this deletes only a single `tabstop` and when using spaces this deletes a single space.\n\nOther values of `virtualedit` don't cause this bug.\n\nThis is a regression from c8dbb04.\n\nP.S.: Thanks for all of your hard work.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n### `minimal.lua`\n\n```lua\nvim.o.virtualedit = 'onemore'\nvim.o.autoindent = true\n\n-- not _NECESSARY_ for reproduction; just for visualization\nvim.o.tabstop = 8\nvim.o.shiftwidth = 32\nvim.o.list = true\n```\n\n### `test.lua`\n\n```lua\nlocal test = {\n    tabs_vs_spaces = 'yes',\n}\n```\n\n1. `nvim --clean -u minimal.lua test.lua`\n2. `o<Esc>`\n3. notice the indentation added by `autoindent` isn't deleted entirely\n4. `:set virtualedit=none` (or any value other than `onemore`)\n5. `o<Esc>`\n6. notice the whole indentation is deleted \n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIf `autoindent` inserts indentation on a line and then you press `<Esc>` without typing anything on that line, the whole indentation should be deleted again.\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\nNVIM v0.13.0-dev-685+gd42f7ee9dc\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nyes, VIM 9.2\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nArch Linux (7.0.11-arch1-1)\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm 20240928-215536-a2f2c07a\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nwezterm\n\n### Installation\n\nAUR: neovim-git",
